<div id="review_243461388" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/243461388" />
    <a title="Gary  the Bookworm" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7036337-gary-the-bookworm"><img alt="Gary  the Bookworm" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1491094498p2/7036337.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/243461388?book_show_action=true">Dec 05, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gary  the Bookworm" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gary  the Bookworm" href="/user/show/7036337-gary-the-bookworm">Gary  the Bookworm</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer243461388" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18280271286140449789">In <i>March, </i> Geraldine Brooks imaginatively writes a back story for <a href='https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Women' rel='nofollow noopener'>Little Women</a> by turning a beloved children&apos;s novel into an adult <i>tour de force.</i> She takes on many of the critical social issues facing Americans in the Nineteenth Century and weaves them into the lives of the fictitious March family.<br/><br/> <a href='http://media.photobucket.com/image/little%20women/quintopatruno/Women/littlewomen.jpg' target='_blank' rel='nofollow noopener'>
  <img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380364380i/716037.jpg' alt='Photobucket Pictures, Images and Photos' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/>
</a><br/>. <br/><br/>The mostly absent father from <i>Little Women</i> takes center stage and confronts the prevailing moral crisis of the day-slavery and the <a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abolitionism' rel='nofollow noopener'> abolitionist </a>response. Real historical figures are introduced </span>
  <span id="freeText18280271286140449789" style="display:none">In <i>March, </i> Geraldine Brooks imaginatively writes a back story for <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Little_Women" rel="nofollow noopener">Little Women</a> by turning a beloved children's novel into an adult <i>tour de force.</i> She takes on many of the critical social issues facing Americans in the Nineteenth Century and weaves them into the lives of the fictitious March family.<br><br> <a href="http://media.photobucket.com/image/little%20women/quintopatruno/Women/littlewomen.jpg" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380364380i/716037.jpg" alt="Photobucket Pictures, Images and Photos" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a><br>. <br><br>The mostly absent father from <i>Little Women</i> takes center stage and confronts the prevailing moral crisis of the day-slavery and the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abolitionism" rel="nofollow noopener"> abolitionist </a>response. Real historical figures are introduced and the interaction between fact and fiction makes for an unforgettable reading experience. This is outstanding historical fiction.<br><br> <a href="http://media.photobucket.com/image/abolition/kate-face/School%20Shnike/ugrrcola.jpg" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1380364380i/716038.jpg" alt="Photobucket Pictures, Images and Photos" class="gr-hostedUserImg">
</a></span>
