  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_284646963" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/284646963" />
    <a title="Margaret" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/991805-margaret"><img alt="Margaret" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1207023483p2/991805.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/284646963?book_show_action=true">Feb 26, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Margaret" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Margaret" href="/user/show/991805-margaret">Margaret</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">All lovers of serious historical fiction</span></div>

        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/991805-margaret?shelf=book-club">book-club</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer284646963" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16064442285459447296">Having loved Caleb&apos;s crossing, I decided to check out all of Brooks&apos; novels. March is another excellent book. Alcott gave us relatively little about Meg, Jo, Beth, and Amy&apos;s father, and Brooks uses this book to imagine his life on the front during the Civil War. March served as a clergyman for the Union troops, and Brooks takes us directly into the war. But we do not have to stay there as she effectively uses flashbacks to fill in all the details we Little Women fans want to know about how he me</span>
  <span id="freeText16064442285459447296" style="display:none">Having loved Caleb's crossing, I decided to check out all of Brooks' novels. March is another excellent book. Alcott gave us relatively little about Meg, Jo, Beth, and Amy's father, and Brooks uses this book to imagine his life on the front during the Civil War. March served as a clergyman for the Union troops, and Brooks takes us directly into the war. But we do not have to stay there as she effectively uses flashbacks to fill in all the details we Little Women fans want to know about how he met his future wife. In addition, Brooks takes us to other sites and times. For the character of Mr. March, Brooks researched Bronson Alcott, Louisa May's father, and embeds details from Bronson's life into the novel. As she did in Caleb's Crossing, she tries to recreate the language of the time. This is simply the best sort of historical novel there is, as it doesn't rely on using current lingo and interests to frame the structure and content of her books. If you haven't yet, give Geraldine Brooks a try. (First review was 02/26/12.)<br /><br />A second time through (11/28/17). I reread this book, this time with my book club. If possible, I loved the book even more. It’s hard to overstate how strong a writer Brooks is. Her texts look fresh and authentic at once. Here she took a classic of children’s literature, a nineteenth century children’s novel, and added a new dimension by expanding on the character of Mr. March. He is hardly the overly sentimental character that so many in Alcott’s classic are. And despite the fact that we want him to be the perfect abolitionist and head of household we want Jo's father to be, Brooks insists on making him a human being with flaws and doubts. The plot is far wider ranging than I had remembered it being, even though I’d already thought she created many different experiences for her character over a long span of time. Readers of Brooks historical novels are rarely bored; instead we are shown a wide variety of locations and actions, and a series of surprises throughout. I again recommend this book. The members of my book club were split. Although all value Brooks as a writer, quite a few were disappointed with the character of Mr. Brooks, arguing that he was not a good enough man. I see why they said that, but I have to disagree. He was imperfect and aware of his imperfections. His path was never easy, yet he traveled it as best he could.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16064442285459447296" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


